          evaporator plate alive vs. which signal "the plate is already toast, replace now."</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Steelheart and heavy-duty knowledge</h4>
          <p>Steelheart line HR/HF cabinets show up in LA casinos, convention centers, and cruise-port commissary kitchens.
          Different tolerances and service intervals than the standard HR line — our techs know the split.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4>Jackson warewashing on same visit</h4>
          <p>Jackson NXP undercounters, Avenger door-types, and conveyor machines share service logic across the Alliance.
          We can handle a Hoshizaki ice machine call and a Jackson dishwasher fault on the same visit.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMON PROBLEMS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Common Hoshizaki ice machine and refrigeration problems LA kitchens call us for</h2>
      <p>
        Week after week our techs see the same Hoshizaki failure patterns on ice machines, reach-in refrigeration, and
        walk-in cooler / walk-in freezer setups. If any of these sound like what's happening in your kitchen, a same-day
        commercial ice machine repair or commercial refrigerator repair visit will usually resolve it:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li><b>Ice production dropped by half</b> — classic CleanCycle12 sensor or water-inlet solenoid issue; scale
          buildup on the probe assembly is the LA-specific culprit.</li>
        <li><b>KM-series cuber not making ice at all</b> — float switch, water regulator, or a failed hot-gas valve on the
          harvest cycle.</li>
        <li><b>F-series flaker cycling but no ice output</b> — auger motor, gearbox bearing, or thermistor probe on the
          evaporator head.</li>
        <li><b>HR reach-in warm in the middle compartment</b> — evaporator fan, defrost timer, or condenser fouling
          from the LA service environment.</li>
        <li><b>HF freezer frost buildup around the door seal</b> — gasket failure, heater wire circuit, or door-close
          sensor drift.</li>
        <li><b>Steelheart reach-in compressor short-cycling</b> — condenser dirty (LA dust and grease loading), low
          refrigerant charge, or start-relay failing under load.</li>
        <li><b>DCM ice & water dispenser no-ice fault</b> — agitator motor, ice bridge sensor, or dispenser solenoid.</li>
        <li><b>Jackson NXP undercounter not heating rinse water</b> — heating element, temperature probe, or booster-heat
          thermostat.</li>
        <li><b>Water in the ice bin</b> — defrost timer or drain line clog, common on older KM units.</li>
        <li><b>Ice machine leaking water</b> — water-inlet valve seal, drain line, or condenser-coil leak on older units.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        For the ice-machine-specific diagnostic deep dive, our
        <a href="/brands/hoshizaki-ice-machine-repair/">Hoshizaki ice machine repair page</a> walks through CleanCycle12
        procedures, KM-series fault codes, and commercial ice machine repair cost ranges for each common fix. For the
        broader category, see our <a href="/commercial/ice-machine-repair/">commercial ice machine repair page</a> and
        the <a href="/price-list/commercial-ice-machine-repair-cost/">ice machine repair cost guide</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

